SIT744 Assignment 1: Image Classification with Deep Feedforward Neural Network¶

Due: 8:00 pm (AEST) 19 April 2021 (Monday)

This is an individual assignment. It contributes 30% to your final mark. Read the assignment instruction carefully.

What to submit

This assignment is to be completed individually and submitted to CloudDeakin. By the due date, you are required to submit the following files to the corresponding Assignment (Dropbox) in CloudDeakin:

  1. [YourID]_assignment1_solution.ipynp: This is your Python notebook solution source file.
  2. [YourID]_assingment1_output.html: This is the output of your Python notebook solution exported in HTML format.
  3. Extra files needed to complete your assignment, if any (e.g., images used in your answers).

For example, if your student ID is: 123456, you will then need to submit the following files:

  • 123456_assignment1_solution.ipynp
  • 123456_assignment1_output.html

Marking criteria

Your submission will be marked using the following criteria.

  • Showing good effort through completed tasks.
  • Applying deep learning theory to design suitable deep learning solutions for the tasks.
  • Critically evaluating and reflecting on the pros and cons of various design decisions.
  • Demonstrating creativity and resourcefulness in providing unique individual solutions. (Warning: Highly similar solutions will be investigated for collusion.)
  • Showing attention to details through a good quality assignment report.

Indicative weights of various tasks are provided below, but the assignment will be marked by the overall quality per the above criteria.

Assignment objective¶

This assignment is for you to demonstrate the knowledge in deep learning that you have acquired from the lectures and practical lab materials. Most tasks in this assignment are straightforward applications of the practical materials in weeks 1-5. Going through these materials before attempting this assignment is highly recommended.

In this assignment, you are going to work with the Fashion-MNIST dataset for image recognition. The dataset contains 10 classes of 28x28 grayscale images. You will see some examples in the visualization task below.

This assignment consists of five tasks.

Task 1 Load the data¶

(weight ~5%)

Load the Fashion MNIST dataset (https://github.com/zalandoresearch/fashion-mnist). You may get the data via Keras (keras.datasets) or Tensorflow Datasets (tfds).

# Create train/validate/test splits

# Download dataset to split Training and Testing set
fashion = keras.datasets.fashion_mnist
train, (x_test, y_test) = fashion.load_data()

x_train, y_train = train

x_train = x_train/255
x_test = x_test/255

dataset = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((x_train, y_train))
#dataset

# Split 8000 validation dataset from testing data set
val_count = -8000

x_val = x_train[val_count:]
y_val = y_train[val_count:]
x_train = x_train[:val_count]
y_train = y_train[:val_count]

print('''
"We need to shuffle the training data set to randomly sort this dataset. 
The buffer size is determined by the lenth of the dataset. If the buffer size is
 greater than the dataset size a uniform random shuffle is guaranteed. Else it 
 will set a buffer in the next amount of buffer size samples been set and will 
 randomly select one from these samples."'''
 )

"We need to shuffle the training data set to randomly sort this dataset. 
The buffer size is determined by the lenth of the dataset. If the buffer size is
 greater than the dataset size a uniform random shuffle is guaranteed. Else it 
 will set a buffer in the next amount of buffer size samples been set and will 
 randomly select one from these samples."

Task 4 Construct a deep forward neural network¶

(weight ~35%)

Task 4.1 Setting up a model for training¶

Construct a deep feedforward neural network. You need to decide and report the following configurations:

  • Output layer:
    • How many output nodes?
    • Which activation function?
  • Hidden layers:
    • How many hidden layers?
    • How many nodes in each layer?
    • Which activation function for each layer?
  • Input layer
    • What is the input size?
  • The loss function
  • The metrics for model evaluation (which may be different from the loss function)
  • The optimiser

Justify your model design decisions.

Plot the model structure using keras.utils.plot_model or similar tools.

What is the number of trainable parameters in the model. Explain how the total number can be estimated from the model configurations.

In [4]:
# Define image size
image_size = (28,28)
In [37]:
# Model Construction

model = keras.Sequential([
    keras.layers.Flatten(input_shape=(28, 28)),
    keras.layers.Dense(256, activation='relu'),
    keras.layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    keras.layers.Dense(10)
])

# learning rate schedule
initial_learning_rate = 1e-3
lr_schedule = keras.optimizers.schedules.ExponentialDecay(
    initial_learning_rate, decay_steps=1000, decay_rate=0.9, staircase=True
)

ADAM = Adam(learning_rate=lr_schedule)

# Model Compile
model.compile(optimizer = ADAM,
              loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(from_logits=True),
              metrics=['accuracy'])
In [124]:
# Visulize Model
plot_model(model, show_shapes=True)

Task 4.2 Fitting the model¶

Before you fit the model. Think about what initialisation method have you chosen? If you did not specify the initialisation method, find out what is the default one. Choose a layer and visualise its initial weights. (Hint: You may use UMAP to visualise a collection of high-dimension vectors.)

Decide and report the following training setting:

  1. The training batch size
  2. The number of training epochs (at least 1,000 epochs recommended)
  3. The learning rate. If you used momentum or a learning rate schedule, please report the configuration as well.

Now fit the model. Show how the training loss changes. How did you decide when to stop training?

After fitting the model, visualise the model weights again. How did the weights change? Why?

!rm -rf ./logs/

from datetime import datetime
import os


epoch_num = 1000
batch_size = 256
log_dir="logs/fit/" + datetime.now().strftime("%Y%m%d-%H%M%S")
tensorboard_callback = tf.keras.callbacks.TensorBoard(log_dir=log_dir, 
                                                      histogram_freq=1,
                                                      )

history = model.fit(x_train, y_train, 
                    epochs=epoch_num, 
                    batch_size = batch_size, 
                    validation_data = (x_val, y_val),
                    callbacks = [tensorboard_callback])

Task 5 Overfitting and regularisation¶

(weight ~30%)

Go back to the previous task. Plot the training and validation loss and accuracy. Answer the following questions:

  1. Do you see overfitting or underfitting? Why?
  2. If you see overfitting, at which epoch did it happen?

Now retrain the model with only 200 training examples. (Make sure that you reinitialise the weights before retraining.) Do you see overfitting? How did the validation loss and accuracy change?

Neural networks are overparametrised models, meaning there can be more parameters than the training examples. Some form of regularisation is almost always necessary to obtain a useful model. Below are some options:

  1. Add dropout
  2. Add Batch Normalisation
  3. Add layer-specific weight regularizations
  4. Change the learning rate

In addition, you may also try changing the weight initialisation method.

Apply different regularisation techniques to the model training. You may also try other techniques for improving training such as learning rate scheduling (see https://www.tensorflow.org/guide/keras/train_and_evaluate#using_learning_rate_schedules).

Run five or more experiments of different training configurations and record the validation accuracy achieved in the Markdown table below. You may modify the table heading to match your experiment design.

Dropout (rate) Batch Normalisation (Y/N) Optimiser Learning Rate Number of Epochs Validation Accuracy

Answer the following questions:

  1. Which configuration achieved the best validation accuracy? Report the test accuracy of your final model.
  2. Which setting had the most impact and which one had the least impact?
In [41]:
# Plot training/validation accuracy and loss

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

acc = history.history['accuracy']
val_acc = history.history['val_accuracy']
loss = history.history['loss']
val_loss = history.history['val_loss']
epochs = range(1, len(acc) + 1)

plt.figure(figsize=(15,4))

ax1 = plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.plot(epochs, loss, label='Training loss')
plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, label='Validation loss')
plt.fill_between(epochs, loss,val_loss,color='g',alpha=.1)

plt.title('Training and validation loss')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.legend()

ax2 = plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.plot(epochs, acc, label='Training accuracy')
plt.plot(epochs, val_acc, label='Validation accuracy')
plt.fill_between(epochs, acc,val_acc,color='g',alpha=.1)
plt.title('Training and validation accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Question1&2 The model could be overfitting because the accuracy and loss flucation in the begining which is the epoch between 0 and 200.

In [140]:
# Training model with 200 samples.

# Download dataset to split Training and Testing set
fashion = keras.datasets.fashion_mnist
train, (x_test, y_test) = fashion.load_data()

x_train, y_train = train

x_train = x_train/255
x_test = x_test/255

# Split 200 from dataset for training
train_count = -200
val_count = -50

x_train200 = x_train[train_count:]
y_train200 = y_train[train_count:]
x_val200 = x_train200[val_count:]
y_val200 = y_train200[val_count:]
In [141]:
# Model Construction

model_200 = keras.Sequential([
    keras.layers.Flatten(input_shape=(28, 28)),
    keras.layers.Dense(256, activation='relu'),
    keras.layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    keras.layers.Dense(10)
])

# learning rate schedule
initial_learning_rate = 1e-3
lr_schedule = keras.optimizers.schedules.ExponentialDecay(
    initial_learning_rate, decay_steps=1000, decay_rate=0.9, staircase=True
)

ADAM = Adam(learning_rate=lr_schedule)

# Model Compile
model_200.compile(optimizer = ADAM,
              loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(from_logits=True),
              metrics=['accuracy'])
In [142]:
# Training model

epoch_num = 1000
batch_size = 256

history_200 = model_200.fit(x_train200, y_train200, 
                    epochs=epoch_num, 
                    batch_size = batch_size, 
                    validation_data = (x_val200, y_val200))

In [145]:
# Plot training/validation accuracy and loss

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

acc = history_200.history['accuracy']
val_acc = history_200.history['val_accuracy']
loss = history_200.history['loss']
val_loss = history_200.history['val_loss']
epochs = range(1, len(acc) + 1)

plt.figure(figsize=(15,4))

ax1 = plt.subplot(221)
plt.plot(epochs, loss, label='Training loss')
plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, label='Validation loss')
plt.fill_between(epochs, loss,val_loss,color='g',alpha=.1)

plt.title('Training and validation loss')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.legend()

ax2 = plt.subplot(222)
plt.plot(epochs, acc, label='Training accuracy')
plt.plot(epochs, val_acc, label='Validation accuracy')
plt.fill_between(epochs, acc,val_acc,color='g',alpha=.1)
plt.title('Training and validation accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

By training the model with 200 samples. The model is not overfitting anymore. However due too the sample data is too small the accuracy of the model is much less than before.

# Split data for training and validation

# Download dataset to split Training and Testing set
fashion = keras.datasets.fashion_mnist
train, (x_test, y_test) = fashion.load_data()

x_train, y_train = train

x_train = x_train/255
x_test = x_test/255

# Split 8000 validation dataset from testing data set
val_count = -8000

#Validation data
x_val = x_train[val_count:]
y_val = y_train[val_count:]
# Training data
x_train = x_train[:val_count]
y_train = y_train[:val_count]

from keras.layers import Dropout

# Create model with drop out
dropout = keras.Sequential()
dropout.add(keras.layers.Flatten(input_shape=(28, 28)))

dropout.add(keras.layers.Dense(256, activation='relu'))
dropout.add(Dropout(0.50))  # Add drop out

dropout.add(keras.layers.Dense(256, activation='relu')) 
dropout.add(Dropout(0.50))  # Add drop out

dropout.add(keras.layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))



# Model Compile
dropout.compile(optimizer = 'adam',
              loss=tf.keras.losses\
              .SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(
             from_logits=True
            ),
              metrics=['accuracy']
    )

# Visulize Model
plot_model(dropout, show_shapes=True)

                    epochs = epoch_num, 
                    batch_size = batch_size, 
                    validation_data = (x_val, y_val))

# Import package
from keras.layers import BatchNormalization

# Create model with batch normalization
batch_norm = keras.Sequential()
batch_norm.add(keras.layers.Flatten(input_shape=(28, 28)))

batch_norm.add(keras.layers.Dense(256, activation='relu'))
batch_norm.add(BatchNormalization())

batch_norm.add(keras.layers.Dense(256, activation='relu')) 
batch_norm.add(BatchNormalization())

batch_norm.add(keras.layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))



# Model Compile
batch_norm.compile(optimizer = 'adam',
              loss=tf.keras.losses\
              .SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(
                  from_logits=True
              ),
              metrics=['accuracy']
        )

# Visulize Model
plot_model(batch_norm, show_shapes=True)

                    epochs=epoch_num, 
                    batch_size = batch_size, 
                    validation_data = (x_val, y_val))

In [7]:
# Add layer-specific weight regularizations

from tensorflow.keras import regularizers

regularizer = keras.Sequential()
regularizer.add(keras.layers.Flatten(input_shape=(28, 28)))

regularizer.add(keras.layers.Dense(256, 
    kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l1(0.01),
    activity_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.01),
    activation='relu'))

regularizer.add(keras.layers.Dense(256, 
    kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l1(0.01),
    activity_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.01),
    activation='relu'))

regularizer.add(keras.layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))



# Model Compile
regularizer.compile(optimizer = 'adam',
              loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(from_logits=True),
              metrics=['accuracy'])

# Visulize Model
plot_model(regularizer, show_shapes=True)

# Training regularizer Model

history_regularizer = regularizer.fit(x_train, y_train, 
                    epochs=epoch_num, 
                    batch_size = batch_size, 
                    validation_data = (x_val, y_val))

In [9]:
# Change the learning rate via Learning Rate schedule

L_R = keras.Sequential([
    keras.layers.Flatten(input_shape=(28, 28)),
    keras.layers.Dense(256, activation='relu'),
    keras.layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    keras.layers.Dense(10)
])

# learning rate schedule
initial_learning_rate = 1e-3
lr_schedule = keras.optimizers.schedules.ExponentialDecay(
    initial_learning_rate, decay_steps=1000, decay_rate=0.9, staircase=True
)

ADAM = Adam(learning_rate=lr_schedule)

# Model Compile
L_R.compile(optimizer = ADAM,
              loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(from_logits=True),
              metrics=['accuracy'])

# Visulize Model
plot_model(L_R, show_shapes=True)

In [11]:
# Weight Initialization Method

initializer = tf.keras.initializers.HeNormal()

HeNorm = keras.Sequential()
HeNorm.add(keras.layers.Flatten(input_shape=(28, 28)))

HeNorm.add(keras.layers.Dense(256, kernel_initializer=initializer, activation='relu'))

HeNorm.add(keras.layers.Dense(256, kernel_initializer=initializer, activation='relu')) 

HeNorm.add(keras.layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))



# Model Compile
HeNorm.compile(optimizer = 'adam',
              loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(from_logits=True),
              metrics=['accuracy'])

# Visulize Model
plot_model(HeNorm, show_shapes=True)

                    epochs=epoch_num, 
                    batch_size = batch_size, 
                    validation_data = (x_val, y_val))

# Summary of the test accuracy of the 5 models

# Evaluate the model on the test data using `evaluate
columns = ['Method',	
  'Optimiser',
  'Learning Rate',
  'Number of Epochs',
  'Validation Accuracy',
  'Test Loss',
  'Test Accuracy']

method = ['Drop Out',
          'Batch Normalisation',
          'weight regularizations',
          'Learning Rate Schedule',
          'He Weight Initializer']

Optimiser = ['Adam'] * 5

epoch = [100]*5

LearningRate = [0.001, 0.001, 0.001, 4.6288e-13, 0.001]

# Create validation accuracy list
val_accuracy = []
val_accuracy.append(max(history_dropout.history['accuracy']))
val_accuracy.append(max(history_batch_norm.history['accuracy']))
val_accuracy.append(max(history_regularizer.history['accuracy']))
val_accuracy.append(max(history_L_R.history['accuracy']))
val_accuracy.append(max(history_He.history['accuracy']))

# Create test accuracy list
test_accuracy = []
test_accuracy.append(dropout.evaluate(x_test, y_test, batch_size=batch_size))
test_accuracy.append(batch_norm.evaluate(x_test, y_test, batch_size=batch_size))
test_accuracy.append(regularizer.evaluate(x_test, y_test, batch_size=batch_size))
test_accuracy.append(L_R.evaluate(x_test, y_test, batch_size=batch_size))
test_accuracy.append(HeNorm.evaluate(x_test, y_test, batch_size=batch_size))

test_acc = pd.DataFrame(test_accuracy)
